// Higher-order functions over a collection, ON THE SUBSTRATE — first-class
// function values (named functions AND inline arrows) folded across an array of
// number-vectors with `foreach`.
//
// One `reduce` expresses every fold: the BEHAVIOUR is passed in as a function
// value. This is the payoff of first-class functions (shipped 2026-06-20):
// behaviour-as-data, closure-free (arrows desugar to hoisted top-level
// functions; captured locals lift to parameters — Sutra has no runtime closure).
//
// NOTE the values are `vector` (number-vectors via `make_real`), NOT `int`.
// That is deliberate: `int` literals fold on the HOST (Python arithmetic), so an
// int version would not be a substrate demonstration. With number-vectors the
// fold runs on the substrate — `reduce` returns a vector, decoded off the real
// axis. (Integrity: every op runs where the spec says it runs.)

// vadd / vsum: substrate vector addition (the `+` is element-wise on the
// number-vectors, on the substrate).
function vector vadd(vector a, vector b) { return a + b; }

// reduce: fold [1,2,3] left-to-right with `f`, starting from `init`. `foreach`
// is the substrate-pure array walk; `f` (a function value) is applied each step.
function vector reduce(function f, vector init) {
    vector acc = init;
    foreach (vector x in [make_real(1.0), make_real(2.0), make_real(3.0)]) {
        acc = f(acc, x);
    }
    return acc;
}

// Same reduce, two behaviours — one named, one inline arrow — both substrate.
function vector total()      { return reduce(vadd, make_real(0.0)); }                          // 1+2+3        = 6
function vector total_dbl()  { return reduce((vector a, vector b) => a + b + b, make_real(0.0)); } // 2*(1+2+3)  = 12

function vector main() {
    return total();
}
